bib_record.title: Measurement of the neutron-induced capture-to-fission cross section ratio in 233U at LANSCE

free_txt: LANSCE
The DANCE detector for detection of gamma-rays,
an array composed of 160 BaF2 crystals covering a
solid angle of approximately 3.5 pi with a single
gamma-ray efficiency of 85%.
The crystals are in four shapes, each 15 cm deep and
covering the same solid angle.
The NEUANCE detector for detection of prompt
fission neutrons, an array consists of 21 stilbene
organic scintillator crystals, installed in the
central cavity of the DANCE array.
The NEUANCE efficiency for a single fission neutron
LANSCE
800 MeV protons on tungsten target with water
as moderator
The DANCE setup is located at the Flight Path 14
of the Lujan Neutron Scattering Center at ~20 m from
the spallation target.
A physics event was defined by all detector
signals found within a coincidence window of 10 ns
for the DANCE crystals and 25 ns for coincidences
between DANCE and NEUANCE.
The nominal 5 mm diameter, 20 mg 233U sample in the
form of solid oxide was stippled on a 0.3 mil Kapton
tape, sealed by another Kapton tape and introduced in
a standard DANCE target holder.
The sample under study is placed in the center of
DANCE, under vacuum in the interior of the beam pipe.
Correction for captures of scattered neutrons by
materials (primarily Ba in DANCE crystals) was
performed with the scaling uncertainty of 2%.
Esther Leal-Cidoncha (2023-10-03):
This scaling introduces 2% systematic uncertainty in
the alpha value.
